commentBody:
@Joe 
Agreeing as a native of Derby (which is not pronounced like you do the race, Americans, it's an 'a' sound). 
I'm sure there are relevant colouring books but the ice cream rec for anyone who might find themselves in the region is Bluebells. They have a nice farm you can visit and the ice cream is available in a lot of tourist sites.

@Matt

As I was replying to the proselytizer yesterday, I was getting lunch at a cafe. I almost went for the vegan curry roll, but there was this beautiful pulled beef sandwich sitting next to it on the counter, meat bursting moistly from between the bread. I couldn't help but ogle.

It was delicious.

@Andrzej

Well, you were wee then.

What's wee on you now we have no way of knowing.

@lucky13

I grew up in New York, and one of my favorite childhood treats was a tall glass of vanilla ice cream with a foamy pour-over of root beer, eaten with a long handled spoon. We called this a root beer float. 

And where *don’t* hamburgers arrive with lettuce, tomato, mustard and mayo? (OK, some places leave off the mayo, but if it’s takeout I add it at home.) I’ve never had an egg cream, so nothing to offer there.

@Heidi

Over here we have neither root beer nor floats, and hamburgers usually include lettuce and tomato, but as for the sauces, they rarely include plain mustard, and I don't think I've ever seen a burger served with mayo in Poland. Personally I can't see how mayo would be a good pairing with a burger 🤷

Isn't it interesting how our cultures differ even when they appear to be similar at first glance?

@lucky13
Bizarre. I grew up in New Jersey, and a "float" always referred to soda with ice cream in it, usually root beer or orange soda.

But when we moved to South Dakota we quickly discovered (literally on day one) that if you go to a Midwestern pizza place and order a "plain pie" they will have no idea what you mean. Out here they call it a "cheese pizza." And they will cut it into squares, even if you beg them not to.

@Heidi

Pizzas here are typically round, unless they make it Detroit style, which are square and cut into squares. In my experience here and in WI, only thin crust pizzas are cut into squares. Thicker crust pizzas are typically triangle shaped pieces. 

Personally, I like the weird little edges on thin cut, which is great because my husband prefers the extra cheesy inside pieces without the outer crust. We're both winning!!

@NanuNanu
It must be a California thing.   I'm born and raised here and have always said HEIGHTH, but I think written height.  Never thought about it until today.

  I guess it's one of those words, like gonna, coulda, shoulda, that is commonly spoken in some places, but not often written.

@Dan 

Huh?
Why?

@fionatimes

I've had an interest in architecture for decades, I've read about it in both Polish and English, and Gothic is my favorite style (over the years I've visited almost all major European Gothic cathedrals, often spending a whole day exploring one) - yet OGEE was a stumper for me today, especially as it crossed with a word that could have been EST(a/e). The fact I wasn't sure if the muscles were ABDUCTORS or ABDUCTeRS didn't help. I needed lookups to make sense of it all.

(I know the Polish name for the arch though: "przeginka" or "ośli grzbiet")

@Hanson
It's his high vowel-to-consonant ratio, of course. Diagnostic of crosswordese.
Exemplars: EPEE, OREO, USE, ORA, ONO, ARIA, etc.

@Petrol

I have considered constructing a puzzle, too, but then I thought how the editors usually seem to change loads of clues - I just would not be able to take that :D

(I mean, I probably wouldn't know how to do that, anyway, but the prospect of having my work meddled with - especially by people who enjoy Kugelman's effluence - is enough to make me not even want to try)

@Andrzej Editors are the best friends you never knew you wanted. 

They’re like the person who discreetly removes your all too visible booger as you proudly prepare to make the speech of your life. 

Feel better about them now?

@Steve L

Do you know what just happened? For the first time in 3 years you criticized a clue more harshly than I did! Soon you'll be peppering your posts with phi's.

(I didn't like it, either, but I get how it was accepted)

@Andrzej

For something to be "wrong," there has to be a discernible reason.  (And when other commenters post about those "wrong" clues, I point out why they're intentionally the way they are.)  

I didn't see any reason here.

@Grumpy

